@infiltr80r¬†- You seem to be beyond what they are capable of. ¬†Googles self driving cars are Lexus SUVs with $100,000 with of electronics strapped to them. ¬†They have not been tested in rain or snow due to safety concerns. ¬†They also rely on PRE-PROGRAMMED ROUTE DATA, they program them for where they are going, the thing does not learn and make decisions much as it goes like a human. ¬†They also have trouble discerning obstacles with current technology fitted to them. ¬†They also always have a driver ready to make corrections and a Google Engineer in the passenger seat. ¬†These things have not been driving around with no one in them, learning the roads and doing it at the same speed we do as they use an excessively cautionary mode, nor can they do it in all conditions. ¬†Also, the fact they have 23 vehicles and they have been in 14 collisions is not very good stats, 61% collision chance per vehicle sucks. ¬†Only one was involving the driver taking control of the vehicle. ¬†What you are describing and expecting is what they expect to achieve by 2020.

As far as driving being routine, it has routine elements, but the overall task itself is not routine. ¬†You have lights that you may or may not have to stop at, different routes to choose from, traffic, accidents, break-down's, police stops, construction, other drivers who are not the same every single time you go driving. ¬†The list goes on and on. ¬†Its easy to see why people think stuff is routine, but many things we consider routine are not. ¬†If very low-level tasks were routine and a computer could do them, they would. ¬†You are dumbing it down to an over-simplistic level, but self driving cars are not going to be Braitenberg vehicles. ¬†Janitorial work seems routine as well, mop the floors here, then here, empty these trash cans in this order, etc, but in the long run, even that is not routine. ¬†Someone pukes, someone spills coffee, there is a dead mouse in a mouse trap today, etc. ¬†Even look at Roombas, those $800 robot vacuum cleaners, they do vacuum whole rooms and avoid running into things and falling down stairs, but they grab dog shit and drag it all over the place without a care. ¬†One non-routine thing and they become shit spreaders. ¬†If you have nothing non-routine, they work fine, as soon as you add in one thing that is not routine, in this case dog shit, the entire concept, the entire function and purpose of it ceases. Driving is probably one of the most non-routine tasks, and you want a computer to do it.

The fact you don't understand what is considered routine and non-routine I call bullshit you deal with automation, and if you do you probably suck at your job. ¬†If you do somehow deal with automation, you deal with stuff that is routine, but you still do not understand non-routine tasks.Ôªø

